opedia |editor=Jill Maynard |title=Drunkenness |encyclopedia=Illustrated Dictionary of Bible Life & Times|publisher=The Reader's Digest Association|location=Pleasantville, New York|date=1997a}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |editor=Jill Maynard |title=Wine |encyclopedia=Illustrated Dictionary of Bible Life & Times|publisher=The Reader's Digest Association|location=Pleasantville, New York|date=1997b}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |editor=Jill Maynard |title=Wine Making |encyclopedia=Illustrated Dictionary of Bible Life & Times|publisher=The Reader's Digest Association|location=Pleasantville, New York|date=1997c}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EchvNjm6alIC&pg=PP14#PRA9-PA1010,M1 |title=Wine |author=John McClintock |author2=James Strong |publisher=Harper and Brothers | location=New York |year=1891 |encyclopedia=Cyclopaedia of Biblical, Theological, and Ecclesiastical Literature |volume=X |pages=1010\u20131017|author2-link=James Strong (theologian) |author-link=John McClintock (theologian) }}\n* {{cite encyclopedia| encyclopedia=Harper's Encyclopedia of Bible Life| title=The Life of the Farmer: Land Use and Crops| authors=M. S. and J. L. Miller revising B. M. Bennett, Jr. and D. H. Scott| publisher=Castle Books| edition=3rd| year=1996| isbn=0-7858-0726-8| url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780785807261}}\n* {{cite book|author=Leon Morris |title=The Gospel According to John |chapter=Additional Note H: The Last Supper and the Passover |edition=revised |publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans |year=1995 |isbn=978-0-8028-2504-9 |series=New International Commentary on the New Testament|author-link=Leon Morris }}\n* {{cite web| url=http://www.studylight.org/lex/grk/ |title=''The New Testament Greek Lexicon'' (based on ''Thayer's'' and ''Smith's Bible Dictionary'' plus others) | accessdate=2007-01-22| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070121143827/http://www.studylight.org/lex/grk/| archivedate= 21 January 2007 | url-status= live}}\n* {{cite web| url=http://www.studylight.org/lex/heb/ |title= The Old Testament Hebrew Lexicon (based on the Brown, Driver, Briggs, Gesenius Hebrew and English Lexicon) | accessdate=2007-01-22| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070117234903/http://www.studylight.org/lex/heb/| archivedate= 17 January 2007 | url-status= live}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=[[Evangelical Dictionary of Theology]]|editor=Walter A. Elwell|author=R. V. Pierard|title=Alcohol, Drinking of|publisher=Baker Book House|location=Grand Rapids, MI|year=1984|isbn=0-8010-3413-2|url=https://archive.org/details/evangelicaldicti00elwe}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Spirit of the Reformation Study Bible | publisher=Zondervan | year=2003 | isbn=978-0-310-92360-2| first1=Richard L. |last1= Pratt | authorlink1=Richard L. Pratt }}\n* {{cite book |author=I. W. Raymond |title=The Teaching of the Early Church on the Use of Wine and Strong Drink |year=1970 |publisher=AMS Press |isbn=978-0-404-51286-6 |origyear=1927}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia| encyclopedia=Theological Dictionary of the New Testament |volume=V|author=Heinrich Seesemann| editor=[[Gerhard Kittel]] and Ronald E. Pitkin | others=trans. Geoffrey W. Bromiley | year= 1967 | publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans | title=\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2| isbn=0-8028-2247-9}}\n* {{cite book |author=Joseph Henry Thayer |title=A Greek-English Lexicon of the New Testament |url=https://archive.org/details/greekenglishlex000grim |url-access=registration |year=1977 |publisher=Baker|isbn=0-8010-8872-0 |origyear=1901|author-link=Joseph Henry Thayer }}\n* {{cite web| url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/jud/tbr/tbr38.htm |title=Tractate Berakoth 6.1 |accessdate=2007-03-15}}\n* {{cite book|author=Bruce Waltke|title=The Book Of Proverbs: Chapters 1\u201315 | publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans | year=2004 | isbn=978-0-8028-2545-2 |series=New International Commentary on the Old Testament|author-link=Bruce Waltke }}\n* {{cite book|author=Bruce Waltke |title=The Book of Proverbs: Chapters 15\u201331 |isbn=978-0-8028-2776-0 |publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans |year=2005 |series=New International Commentary on the Old Testament}}\n* {{cite book|author=Jeff Yelton |title=Wine in the Lord's Supper|publisher=self-published |year=2019}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Alcohol and health}}\n{{Portal|Drink|Christianity}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alcohol In The Bible}}\n[[Category:Biblical topics]]\n[[Category:Oenology]]\n[[Category:Judaism and alcohol]]\n[[Category:Christianity and alcohol]]\n", "name_user": "LayLielit", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_in_the_Bible"}
{"title_page": "Pitlessie", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| official_name = Pitlessie\n| country = Scotland\n| static_image = File:Pitlessie, Cults Panorama.jpg\n| static_image_alt = Pitlessie, seen from Cults Hill\n| static_image_caption = Pitlessie, seen from Cults Hill\n| population = 325\n| edinburgh_distance_mi = 23\n| post_town = CUPAR\n| population_ref = (2010 estimate)<ref name=\"Fife Greenspace Strategy\">{{cite web|publisher=Fife Council |date=November 2010 |title=Fife Greenspace Strategy 2011 - 2016 |format=PDF  |url=http://publications.fifedirect.org.uk/c64_FifeGreenspaceStrategy2011-2016.pdf }}</ref>\n| coordinates = {{coord|56.275|N|3.076|W|}}\n| constituency_scottish_parliament = [[North East Fife (Scottish Parliament constituency)|North East Fife]]\n| constituency_westminster = [[North East Fife (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Fife]]\n| lieutenancy_scotland = [[Fife]]\n| postcode_area = KY\n| postcode_district = KY15\n| os_grid_reference = NO335096\n| unitary_scotland = [[Fife]]\n}}{{Use dmy dates|date = April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date = April 2019}}\n\n'''Pitlessie''' is a small village in [[Cults, Fife|Cults]], [[Fife]], Scotland. It is roughly {{convert|4+1/2|mi|km|round=0.5}} southwest of the nearest large town, [[Cupar]], and {{convert|23|mi|km|abbr=off}} north of Edinburgh. It had an estimated population of 325 in 2010.<ref name=\"Fife Greenspace Strategy\">{{cite web|publisher=Fife Council |date=November 2010 |title=Fife Greenspace Strategy 2011 - 2016 |format=PDF  |url=http://publications.fifedirect.org.uk/c64_FifeGreenspaceStrategy2011-2016.pdf }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nAs the only village in the parish of Cults, it remained fairly small until it became the home of the Priestfield Maltings. Built in 1890, the maltings were acquired by the Bonthrone family in 1937, owners of similar businesses in the area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6rg1b_KpnPs|title=Old Photographs Of Pitlessie Fife Scotland|last=|first=|date=|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It once produced over 2,000 tonnes of malt and employed 14 men. Production remained in action until 1968 when the owners at that time, Scottish Malt Distillers, changed strategies. The category B listed building has since been converted into housing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kaskwhisky.com/priestfield-maltings/|title=Priestfield Maltings in Pitlessie in Fife - Kask Whisky|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\nThe Pitlessie [[:Category:Flower shows|Flower Show]] is a yearly event which takes place in the late summer. Originally an evening show ran by the Highland Games Committee, the show hosts many competitions for locals and those from afar of all ages, and is funded through the support of those in the local community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pitlessieflowershow.org.uk/|title=Home|last=|first=|date=|website=Pitlessie Flower Show|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Landmarks ==\nThe Sir David Wilkie Memorial Hall was constructed in 1897 in the style of a Georgian Chapel.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gifford|first=John|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3Hz5ZtShXvoC&pg=PA344|title=Fife|publisher=Yale University Press|year=1988|isbn=|location=|pages=344}}</ref> Outside it is a war memorial to the men in the parish who were killed in the world wars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scottishchurches.org.uk/sites/site/id/10416|title=Sir David Wilkie Memorial Hall - Cults, Fife - Places of Worship in Scotland {{!}} SCHR|last=|first=|date=|website=Scottish Churches|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nPitlessie Primary School, founded in 1860, serves Pitlessie, the parish of Cults and a portion of the [[Howe of Fife]]. The school, along with Craigrothie Primary, is led by Tamsin Frost and is attended by a single class of under 20 pupils. Secondary school aged pupils attend the nearby [[Bell Baxter High School]] in [[Cupar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifedirect.org.uk/PitlessiePS|title=Pitlessie Primary School - Welcome to Pitlessie Primary School|last=|first=|date=|website=Pitlessie Primary School Website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Notable Residents ==\nThe village was the birthplace of artist [[David Wilkie (artist)|David Wilkie]] who also attended school in the village, son to the parish minister. After returning from the [[Edinburgh College of Art|Trustees' Academy]] in 1804, in one of his earliest works, he depicted the scenes of Pitlessie Fair which included many of his family members and neighbours. A large reproduction of this painting now hangs above the stage in the Sir David Wilkie Memorial Hall, which was built in his memory.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://goo.gl/maps/QeYtv Google Earth view of Pitlessie]\n*[http://goo.gl/maps/A4mDc Google Earth view of Cults]\n\n{{coord|56.275|-3.076|type:city_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Fife]]\n\n\n{{Fife-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| official_name = Pitlessie\n| country = Scotland\n| static_image = Pitlessie - geograph.org.uk - 153984.jpg\n| static_image_alt = Pitlessie, seen from Cults Hill\n| static_image_caption = Pitlessie, seen from Cults Hill\n| population = 325\n| edinburgh_distance_mi = 23\n| static_image_width = 240px\n| post_town = CUPAR\n| population_ref = (2010 estimate)<ref name=\"Fife Greenspace Strategy\">{{cite web|publisher=Fife Council |date=November 2010 |title=Fife Greenspace Strategy 2011 - 2016 |format=PDF  |url=http://publications.fifedirect.org.uk/c64_FifeGreenspaceStrategy2011-2016.pdf }}</ref>\n| coordinates = {{coord|56.275|N|3.076|W|}}\n| constituency_scottish_parliament = [[North East Fife (Scottish Parliament constituency)|North East Fife]]\n| constituency_westminster = [[North East Fife (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Fife]]\n| lieutenancy_scotland = [[Fife]]\n| postcode_area = KY\n| postcode_district = KY15\n| os_grid_reference = NO335096\n| unitary_scotland = [[Fife]]\n}}{{Use dmy dates|date = April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date = April 2019}}\n\n'''Pitlessie''' is a small village in [[Cults, Fife|Cults]], [[Fife]], Scotland. It is roughly {{convert|4+1/2|mi|km|round=0.5}} southwest of the nearest large town, [[Cupar]], and {{convert|23|mi|km|abbr=off}} north of Edinburgh. It had an estimated population of 325 in 2010.<ref name=\"Fife Greenspace Strategy\">{{cite web|publisher=Fife Council |date=November 2010 |title=Fife Greenspace Strategy 2011 - 2016 |format=PDF  |url=http://publications.fifedirect.org.uk/c64_FifeGreenspaceStrategy2011-2016.pdf }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nAs the only village in the parish of Cults, it remained fairly small until it became the home of the Priestfield Maltings. Built in 1890, the maltings were acquired by the Bonthrone family in 1937, owners of similar businesses in the area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6rg1b_KpnPs|title=Old Photographs Of Pitlessie Fife Scotland|last=|first=|date=|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It once produced over 2,000 tonnes of malt and employed 14 men. Production remained in action until 1968 when the owners at that time, Scottish Malt Distillers, changed strategies. The category B listed building has since been converted into housing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kaskwhisky.com/priestfield-maltings/|title=Priestfield Maltings in Pitlessie in Fife - Kask Whisky|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\nThe Pitlessie [[:Category:Flower shows|Flower Show]] is a yearly event which takes place in the late summer. Originally an evening show ran by the Highland Games Committee, the show hosts many competitions for locals and those from afar of all ages, and is funded through the support of those in the local community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pitlessieflowershow.org.uk/|title=Home|last=|first=|date=|website=Pitlessie Flower Show|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Landmarks ==\nThe Sir David Wilkie Memorial Hall was constructed in 1897 in the style of a Georgian Chapel.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gifford|first=John|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3Hz5ZtShXvoC&pg=PA344|title=Fife|publisher=Yale University Press|year=1988|isbn=|location=|pages=344}}</ref> Outside it is a war memorial to the men in the parish who were killed in the world wars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scottishchurches.org.uk/sites/site/id/10416|title=Sir David Wilkie Memorial Hall - Cults, Fife - Places of Worship in Scotland {{!}} SCHR|last=|first=|date=|website=Scottish Churches|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nPitlessie Primary School, founded in 1860, serves Pitlessie, the parish of Cults and a portion of the [[Howe of Fife]]. The school, along with Craigrothie Primary, is led by Tamsin Frost and is attended by a single class of under 20 pupils. Secondary school aged pupils attend the nearby [[Bell Baxter High School]] in [[Cupar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifedirect.org.uk/PitlessiePS|title=Pitlessie Primary School - Welcome to Pitlessie Primary School|last=|first=|date=|website=Pitlessie Primary School Website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Notable Residents ==\nThe village was the birthplace of artist [[David Wilkie (artist)|David Wilkie]] who also attended school in the village, son to the parish minister. After returning from the [[Edinburgh College of Art|Trustees' Academy]] in 1804, in one of his earliest works, he depicted the scenes of Pitlessie Fair which included many of his family members and neighbours. A large reproduction of this painting now hangs above the stage in the Sir David Wilkie Memorial Hall, which was built in his memory.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://goo.gl/maps/QeYtv Google Earth view of Pitlessie]\n*[http://goo.gl/maps/A4mDc Google Earth view of Cults]\n\n{{coord|56.275|-3.076|type:city_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Fife]]\n\n\n{{Fife-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ethanxlee", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed Image", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pitlessie"}
{"title_page": "Arms (video game)", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Arms<!--Do not capitalize, per MOS:ALLCAPS-->\n| image = Arms (video game).jpg\n| caption = Promotional artwork, featuring Ribbon Girl and Spring Man engaging in combat.\n| developer = [[Nintendo EPD]]\n| publisher = [[Nintendo]]\n| director = {{Unbulleted list|Kenta Sato|Masaaki Ishikawa|Shintaro Jikumaru}}\n| producer = Kosuke Yabuki\n| artist = Masaaki Ishikawa\n| composer = {{Unbulleted list|Atsuko Asahi|Yasuaki Iwata}}\n| platforms = [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| released = June 16, 2017\n| genre = [[Fighting game|Fighting]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Arms'''''|\u30a2\u30fc\u30e0\u30ba|\u0100muzu|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}}<!--Do not capitalize, per MOS:ALLCAPS and MOS:TMCAPS--> is a [[fighting game]] developed and published by [[Nintendo]] for the [[Nintendo Switch]], which released on June 16, 2017. The game differentiates itself from standard fighting games with its unconventional fighting system where every playable character fights with long range attacks, and up to four players can choose a fighter and battle using a variety of extendable, customizable arms to knock out opponents in a three-dimensional arena. By July 2018, the game had sold over two million copies worldwide, making it one of the [[List of best-selling Nintendo Switch video games|best-selling games on the Switch]].\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Arms Gameplay Match.jpg|left|thumb|A match of ''ARMS'' being played between Spring Man and Ribbon Girl.]]\n''Arms'' is a 3D fighting sports game in which up to four players can control one of a variety of fighters, with the player able to perform basic fighting actions using extendable arms such as punching, throwing, blocking, and dodging.<ref name=\"Poly\">{{cite web|last=Frank|first=Allegra|date=January 12, 2017|url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/1/12/14260222/arms-nintendo-switch|title=Arms is a fantasy fighter for Nintendo Switch|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=January 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=January 13, 2017|url=https://www.polygon.com/nintendo-switch/2017/1/13/14263462/nintendo-switch-arms-fighting|title=Arms is the competitive, motion controlled fighting game coming to Nintendo Switch|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=January 13, 2017}}</ref> ''Arms'' features fifteen playable fighters, with five of them being released as [[downloadable content]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gilyadov|first=Alex|date=June 15, 2017|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/06/15/e3-2017-first-arms-dlc-character-revealed|title=E3 2017: First Arms DLC Character Revealed|website=[[IGN]]|accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref> Each fighter starts with three unique Arms that can be selected in battle, but the use of all other fighters' Arms can be unlocked in the Get Arms mode. All fighters also have unique attributes in combat.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ramos|first=Jeff|date=June 16, 2017|url=https://www.polygon.com/arms-guide/2017/6/16/15765392/arms-nintendo-switch-best-character|title=How to choose the best character in Arms|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref> When the attack meter is fully charged, players are able to unleash a high-damage \"rush attack\" against their opponents. Players can also charge their attacks to temporarily increase damage and utilize elemental effects.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nunneley|first=Stephany|date=June 8, 2017|url=https://www.vg247.com/2017/06/08/arms-heres-six-tips-to-help-you-dominate-your-opponents/|title=Arms \u2013 here are six tips to help you dominate opponents|website=[[VG247]]|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref> Each character has a different set of abilities and unique Arms for different strategies. Players are able to use the system's [[Joy-Con]] motion controls or standard button inputs with controllers such as the Pro Controller to operate each Arm individually. Players are also able to customize their Arm load outs, with each Arm being able to be selected independently. Every Arm is different with elemental attributes and varying weights that affect gameplay. Up to four players are able to play in a single match, either in a three or four-way free-for-all, or in a two-on-two mode in which teammates are tethered together.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://arms.nintendo.com/battle/|title=Battle Modes - ARMS for Nintendo|website=[[Nintendo]]|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Karassik|first=Neila|date=June 12, 2017|url=http://www.space.ca/arms-nintendo-switch-game-review/|title=Nintendo Switch's ARMS Is A Knockout - And That's No Stretch|website=Space}}</ref>\n\nBesides the standard fighting mode, ''Arms'' features multiple other modes: Versus, Grand Prix, and a variety of Battle modes. In Grand Prix, players take on a set of 10 matches against computer-controlled fighters to win the championship belt. Battle mode consists of [[volleyball]] and [[basketball]] modes, a target breaking mode, and a survival mode.<ref name=\":0\"/> Players can also play online in a party match lobby with up to 20 players, or in one-on-one ranked matches.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stark|first=Chelsea|date=May 17, 2017|url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/5/17/15655898/arms-nintendo-switch-game-modes|title=Arms' new game modes are a weird take on classic sports|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=June 6, 2017}}</ref> ''Arms'' featured ten playable fighters at launch, with five additional fighters added via post-release updates.<ref>{{cite web |last=Frank |first=Allegra |date=August 22, 2017 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/8/22/16182734/arms-free-demo-playable-characters-lola-pop-trailer |title=Arms\u2019 new fighter is a human balloon animal |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Romano |first=Sal |date=November 15, 2017 |url=https://gematsu.com/2017/11/arms-version-4-0-update-now-available-adds-new-fighter-misango |title=Arms version 4.0 update now available, adds new fighter Misango |website=Gematsu |accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\nThe game was developed by Nintendo's [[Entertainment Planning & Development]] division, produced by Kosuke Yabuki.<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|title=ARMS Dev. Talk - ft. Mr. Yabuki|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aofi13XiVXA|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> In the beginning, the game began as a wish to see if a behind-the-camera perspective could work in a fighting game.<ref name=\":1\" /> To make this idea work, the main feature of extendable arms was implemented, with Yabuki stating \"Let's talk about a game I know about very well - Mario Kart. Something appears in the distance and you steer in relation to that - that's the basic structure of the game,\" in reference to ''[[Mario Kart]]'' and how its gameplay helped influence ''Arms''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-03-22-early-arms-prototypes-showcase-cut-bowling-mini-game|title=Early prototype of Arms revealed, including a cut bowling mini-game|last=Reynolds|first=Matthew|date=2018-03-22|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref>\n\nEarly on, the idea of featuring staple Nintendo characters such as [[Link (The Legend of Zelda)|Link]] and [[Mario]] was considered. However, the aesthetic of the game, especially with the concept of extendable arms, clashed with them, and it was eventually decided that a new cast of characters be created.<ref name=\"VBeat\">{{cite web |last=Webster |first=Andrew |date=June 6, 2017 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/6/6/15746164/nintendo-switch-arms-character-design-interview |title=How Nintendo Created Its Wild New Cast of Fighters for Switch Game Arms |website=[[The Verge]] |accessdate=June 8, 2017}}</ref> The possibility of adding characters from ''[[Punch-Out!!]]'' was also considered but the team was concerned about alienating fans of that franchise and potentially confusing new players.<ref>{{cite web |last=McWhertor |first=Michael |date=March 26, 2018 |url=https://www.polygon.com/interviews/2018/3/26/17164492/arms-nintendo-switch-interview-kosuke-yabuki |title=Arms director Kosuke Yabuki on the past and future of the Switch fighting game |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCharacter designs started with the arms first with the team working backwards to decide what type of character would possess it, for instance the character of Helix, started with the idea of a fighter whose arms were [[DNA]] strands, although the team initially did not know much else about him. Most fighters were designed to fill a gameplay need, although there are some exceptions where a design came first.<ref name=\"VBeat\" /> An early concept for the game had the characters using external devices to punch their opponents; however, this was later dropped in favor of the characters extending their actual arms.<ref name=\"GInformer\">{{cite web |last=Hillard |first=Kyle |date=June 7, 2017 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2017/06/02/-arms-creators-on-twintelles-popularity-and-the-strange-lore-of-the-games-world-luffy-one-piece.aspx |title=Arms' Creators On Twintelle's Popularity And The Strange Lore Of The Game's World |website=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=June 8, 2017}}</ref> Art director Masaaki Ishikawa said that the game's art style was largely influenced by ''[[Dragon Ball]]'' and ''[[Akira (manga)|Akira]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Simon |last2=Davison |first2=John |date=June 14, 2017 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/glixel/features/because-nintendo-arms-producer-explains-why-fighters-have-stretchy-arms-w487949 |title='Because Nintendo': 'Arms' Producer Explains Why Fighters Have Stretchy Arms |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=October 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe game was announced at the Nintendo Switch Presentation on January 12, 2017, and was released worldwide on June 16, 2017.<ref name=Poly/><ref>{{cite web |last=Goldfarb |first=Andrew |date=April 12, 2017 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/04/12/arms-release-date-announced-for-nintendo-switch |title=Splatoon 2 Release Date, Amiibo Set Announced |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=April 12, 2017}}</ref> Prior to the game's release, a multiplayer [[Game demo|demo]] known as the \"''Arms'' Global Testpunch\" was made available for download on the [[Nintendo eShop]], with players being able to test the online gameplay during twelve separate hour-long sessions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://arms.nintendo.com/#global-testpunch |title=ARMS for the Nintendo Switch\u2122 home gaming system \u2013 Official Site |website=[[Nintendo]] |accessdate=May 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Roberts |first=David |date=May 17, 2017 |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/try-out-nintendos-upcoming-switch-fighter-arms-with-two-global-testpunch-events-starting-may-26/ |title=Try out Nintendo's upcoming Switch fighter Arms with two Global Testpunch events, starting May 26 |website=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=May 18, 2017}}</ref> \n\nIrregular post-release updates were released featuring new playable characters, stages, and arms.<ref>{{cite web |author=Nintendo |date=May 17, 2017 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hY2_Xu3f8Bc |title=ARMS Direct 5.17.2017 |website=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=May 18, 2017}}</ref> These free releases of additional content followed ''[[Splatoon]]''{{'s}} update model,<ref>{{Cite web |last=McCarthy |first=Caty |date=May 17, 2017 |url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/arms-unveils-new-characters-modes-global-testpunch-nintendo-direct |title=Arms Unveils New Characters, Modes, a Global Testpunch, and More in Latest Nintendo Direct |website=[[USGamer]] |accessdate=May 18, 2017}}</ref> while the Testpunch demo was also available for use multiple times. The game received new characters and stages by way of downloadable content until December 2017, when Nintendo announced that they would no longer be adding new content to the game other than [[Balance (game design)|balance]] updates.<ref>{{cite web |author=Nintendo |date=December 22, 2017 |url=https://topics.nintendo.co.jp/c/article/67b3f436-e451-11e7-8cda-063b7ac45a6d.html |title=\"Theoretically strongest\" fighter entry! \"ARMS\" Ver. 5 update |website=[[Nintendo]] |accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/nintendos-arms-gets-its-last-new-character-1821529481/|title=Nintendo's Arms Gets Its Last New Character|date=22 December 2017|accessdate=25 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=McWhertor |first=Michael |date=October 5, 2017 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/01/25/nintendo-has-no-plans-for-additional-arms-content |title=NINTENDO HAS 'NO PLANS' FOR ADDITIONAL ARMS CONTENT |website=IGN |accessdate=January 25, 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn May 2018, a demo of the game was released on the eShop for a limited time only. Unlike the Testpunch events, this demo only featured offline modes of single-player and local multiplayer with a limited selection of characters and Arms to choose from.<ref>{{cite web|title=ARMS demo now available|url=https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/arms-demo-now-available|website=Nintendo|accessdate=May 12, 2018|date=May 10, 2018}}</ref> \n\nA temporary Free Game Trial was made available for free to Nintendo Switch Online members from March 26th to April 6th, 2020. This free trial allowed players to experience the entirety of the game's features and modes for the alloted time.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = 77/100<ref name=Metacritic>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/switch/arms |title=ARMS for Switch Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=June 7, 2017}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 7/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Carter |first=Chris |date=June 16, 2017 |url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-arms-438597.phtml |title=Review: Arms |website=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=June 17, 2017}}</ref>\n| Edge = 9/10<ref name=\"Edge\" />\n| EGM = 8.5/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Schaeffer |first=Emma |date=June 7, 2017 |url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/arms-review/|title=Arms Review |website=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGMNow]] |accessdate=June 17, 2017}}</ref>\n| Fam = 33/40<ref name=Fam>{{cite web |last=Romano |first=Sal |date=June 6, 2017 |url=https://gematsu.com/2017/06/famitsu-review-scores-issue-1488 |title=Famitsu Review Scores: Issue 1488 |website=Gematsu |accessdate=June 8, 2017}}</ref>\n| GI = 8.25/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Shea |first=Brian |date=June 7, 2017 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/arms/b/switch/archive/2017/06/07/arms-game-informer-review.aspx |title=Arms Review - Punching Up |website=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=June 17, 2017}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 7/10<ref name=\"GameSpot review\">{{cite web |last=Plagge |first=Kallie |date=June 7, 2017 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/arms-review/1900-6416696/ |title=Arms Review |website=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Schilling |first=Chris |date=June 7, 2017 |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/arms-review/ |title=Arms review: 'An invigorating blend of graceful movement and slapstick violence' |website=[[GamesRadar]]}}</ref>\n| IGN = 8/10<ref name=\"IGN review\">{{cite web |last=Graeber |first=Brendan |date=June 7, 2017 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/06/07/arms-review |title=Arms Review |website=[[IGN]]}}</ref>\n| NLife = {{Rating|9|10}}<ref>{{cite web |last=McFerran |first=Damien |date=June 16, 2017 |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/nintendo-switch/arms |title=Review: Arms (Switch) |website=[[Nintendo Life]] |accessdate=June 17, 2017}}</ref>\n| NWR = 8/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Ronaghan |first=Neal |date=June 7, 2017 |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/44768/arms-switch-review |title=Arms (Switch) Review |website=Nintendo World Report |accessdate=June 17, 2017}}</ref>\n| Poly = 8/10<ref name=\"Polygon review\">{{cite web |last=McWhertor |first=Michael |date=June 7, 2017 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/6/7/15751828/arms-review-nintendo-switch |title=Arms review |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''Hardcore Gamer''\n| rev1Score = 4.5/5<ref>{{cite web |last=Swalley |first=Kirstin |date=June 7, 2017|url=https://www.hardcoregamer.com/2017/06/07/review-arms/259968/|title=Review: ARMS|work=Hardcore Gamer |accessdate=July 20, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAt its announcement, ''Arms'' was compared by critics to the boxing minigame from ''[[Wii Sports]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hardawar |first=Devindra |date=January 12, 2017 |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/01/12/arms-brings-shooter-esque-boxing-to-the-nintendo-switch/ |title='Arms' brings shooter-esque boxing to the Nintendo Switch |website=[[Engadget]] |accessdate=January 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Prell |first=Sam |date=January 12, 2017 |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/switch-game-arms-is-like-boxing-if-boxing-starred-anime-characters-with-slinkies-for-arms/ |title=Switch game Arms is like boxing, if boxing starred anime characters with Slinkies for... arms |website=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=January 13, 2017}}</ref> Jack Sheperd of ''[[The Independent]]'' stated after playing it at a Switch hands-on event that it was one of the \"most impressive\" games on display.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shepherd |first=Jack |date=January 16, 2017 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/gaming/nintendo-switch-hands-on-review-zelda-mario-1-2-switch-arms-breath-of-wind-a7530396.html |title=Nintendo Switch hands-on review: Brilliant device, lacklustre line-up |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=February 22, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]'' compared ''Arms'' with other Nintendo titles and thought that \"''Arms'' is to the fighting game what ''[[Splatoon]]'' is to the online shooter or ''[[Mario Kart]]'' to the [[Racing video game|driving game]]\".<ref name=\"Edge\">{{cite magazine |author=Edge staff |date=April 27, 2017 |url=https://www.pressreader.com/australia/edge/20170427/281483571275804 |title=The art of fighting without fighting? Show me some of it |magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] |accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe game received \"generally favorable\" reviews, according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name=Metacritic /> Brandon Graeber from [[IGN]] praised the game's complexity and addictive nature, but noted the game's lack of content at launch.<ref name=\"IGN review\"/> Michael McWhertor from ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' applauded the game's concept, which he described as creative, and that the game reminded him of the ''[[Punch-Out!!]]'' series, stating that ''Arms'' could become Nintendo's next big franchise.<ref name=\"Polygon review\"/> Kallie Plagge from [[GameSpot]] praised the character roster, but criticized the game's steep [[learning curve]].<ref name=\"GameSpot review\"/>\n\nMultiple publications listed the game as one of the best of 2017.<ref>{{cite web |author=Eurogamer staff |date=December 30, 2017 |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-12-30-eurogamers-top-50-games-of-2017-10-1 |title=Eurogamer's Top 50 Games of 2017: 10-1 |website=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=EGM staff |date=December 27, 2017 |url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/features/egms-best-of-2017-part-one-25-21/ |title=EGM's Best of 2017: Part One: #25 ~ #21 |website=EGMNow |accessdate=January 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180114191051/http://www.egmnow.com/articles/features/egms-best-of-2017-part-one-25-21/ |archive-date=January 14, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Polygon staff |date=December 18, 2017 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2017-best-games/2017/12/18/16781674/best-video-games-2017-top-50-mario-pubg-zelda |title=The 50 best games of 2017 |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref> In ''[[Game Informer]]''{{'}}s Reader's Choice Best of 2017 Awards, the game placed third for \"Best Fighting Game\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Cork |first=Jeff |date=January 4, 2018 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2018/01/04/reader-s-choice-best-of-2017-awards.aspx?PostPageIndex=2 |title=Reader's Choice Best Of 2017 Awards (Page 2) |website=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref> It was also nominated for the same category in [[IGN]]'s Best of 2017 Awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/wikis/best-of-2017-awards/Best_Fighting_Game |title=Best of 2017 Awards: Best Fighting Game |website=[[IGN]] |date=December 20, 2017 |accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref> The game has seen a small, but dedicated [[esports]] scene across multiple regions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://compete.kotaku.com/a-pocket-of-passionate-players-is-the-only-thing-keepin-1821777320|title=A Pocket Of Passionate Players Is The Only Thing Keeping Competitive ARMS Alive|website=Compete|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\n===Sales===\n''Arms'' debuted at number two on the UK sales charts, behind ''[[Horizon Zero Dawn]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Dayus |first=Oscar |date=June 19, 2017 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/top-10-uk-sales-chart-horizon-zero-dawn-beats-swit/1100-6451022/ |title=Top 10 UK Sales Chart: Horizon Zero Dawn Beats Switch's Arms To No.1 |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref> It was number two in Australia, behind the same game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.igea.net/2017/06/top-10-games-for-the-week-ended-18-june-2017/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=July 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729180245/http://www.igea.net/2017/06/top-10-games-for-the-week-ended-18-june-2017/ |archive-date=July 29, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It sold 100,652 physical copies during its first week of release in Japan, and debuted at number one on the all-format sales charts.<ref>{{cite web |last=Romano |first=Sal |date=June 21, 2017 |url=http://gematsu.com/2017/06/media-create-sales-61217-61817 |title=Media Create Sales: 6/12/17 \u2013 6/18/17 |publisher=Gematsu |accessdate=June 23, 2017}}</ref> By September 30, 2018, the game had sold over 2.1 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/finance/software/index.html|title=IR Information : Sales Data - Top Selling Title Sales Units|website=Nintendo Co., Ltd.|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203005532/https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/finance/software/index.html|archive-date=2018-12-03|access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\" | 2017\n| rowspan=\"1\" | [[Game Critics Awards]]\n| Best Fighting Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamecriticsawards.com/nominees.html |title=Game Critics Awards: Best of E3 2017 (2017 Nominees) |website=[[Game Critics Awards]] |accessdate=December 31, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | [[Golden Joystick Awards]]\n| Nintendo Game of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Gaito |first=Eri |date=November 13, 2017 |url=https://www.bestinslot.co/golden-joystick-awards-2017-nominees/ |title=Golden Joystick Awards 2017 Nominees |website=Best in Slot |accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Weber |first=Rachel |date=November 17, 2017 |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/the-legend-of-zelda-breath-of-the-wild-scores-big-at-the-35th-golden-joystick-awards-presented-with-omen-by-hp/ |title=The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild scores big at the 35th Golden Joystick Awards presented with OMEN by HP |website=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | [[The Game Awards 2017]]\n| Best Fighting Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Makuch |first=Eddie |date=December 8, 2017 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-game-awards-2017-winners-headlined-by-zelda-br/1100-6455467/ |title=The Game Awards 2017 Winners Headlined By Zelda: Breath Of The Wild's Game Of The Year |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\" | 2018\n| rowspan=\"1\" | New York Game Awards\n| Central Park Children's Zoo Award for Best Kids Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Whitney |first=Kayla |date=January 25, 2018 |url=https://www.axs.com/complete-list-of-winners-of-the-new-york-game-awards-2018-127527 |title=Complete list of winners of the New York Game Awards 2018 |website=[[AXS (company)|AXS]] |accessdate=January 27, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | [[D.I.C.E. Awards]]\n| Fighting Game of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Makuch |first=Eddie |date=January 14, 2018 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/game-of-the-year-nominees-announced-for-dice-award/1100-6456107/ |title=Game Of The Year Nominees Announced For DICE Awards |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=January 17, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | [[NAVGTR Awards]]\n| Game, Original Fighting\n| {{Won}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |url=http://navgtr.org/archives/3351/ |title=Nominee List for 2017 |website=[[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]] |date=February 9, 2018 |accessdate=February 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180215172210/http://navgtr.org/archives/3351/ |archive-date=February 15, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://navgtr.org/archives/3365/ |title=Horizon wins 7; Mario GOTY |website=[[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]] |date=March 13, 2018 |accessdate=March 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180314070824/http://navgtr.org/archives/3365/ |archive-date=March 14, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Legacy==\nA graphic novel by [[Dark Horse Comics]] based on ''Arms'' is under production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2017/12/19/arms-comic-announced-written-by-ian-flynn.aspx|title=ARMS Comic Announced, Written By Ian Flynn|last=Khan|first=Imran|website=Game Informer|language=en|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/53020/arms-graphic-novel-status-update|title=ARMS Graphic Novel Status Update|last=Berube|first=Justin|website=Nintendo World Report|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> Spring Man appears as an Assist Trophy in the 2018 crossover [[fighting game]] ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]'', as well as an upcoming fighter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20181101005675/en/Super-Smash-Bros.-Ultimate-Nintendo-Direct-Unleashes|title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Nintendo Direct Unleashes New Details|date=2018-11-01|website=www.businesswire.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref><ref>https://www.ign.com/articles/super-smash-bros-ultimates-next-dlc-character-will-be-from-arms</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{officialwebsite|https://web.archive.org/web/20190405165149/https://arms.nintendo.com/}} (archived)\n\n{{Portal bar|Video games}}\n\n[[Category:2017 video games]]\n[[Category:3D fighting games]]\n[[Category:Fighting games used at the Evolution Championship Series tournament]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Entertainment Planning & Development games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch eShop games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch-only games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Wii U games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female antagonists]]\n[[Category:Versus fighting games]]\n[[Category:Split-screen multiplayer games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Arms<!--Do not capitalize, per MOS:ALLCAPS-->\n| image = Arms (video game).jpg\n| caption = Promotional artwork, featuring Ribbon Girl and Spring Man engaging in combat.\n| developer = [[Nintendo EPD]]\n| publisher = [[Nintendo]]\n| director = {{Unbulleted list|Kenta Sato|Masaaki Ishikawa|Shintaro Jikumaru}}\n| producer = Kosuke Yabuki\n| artist = Masaaki Ishikawa\n| composer = {{Unbulleted list|Atsuko Asahi|Yasuaki Iwata}}\n| platforms = [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| released = June 16, 2017\n| genre = [[Fighting game|Fighting]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Arms'''''|\u30a2\u30fc\u30e0\u30ba|\u0100muzu|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}}<!--Do not capitalize, per MOS:ALLCAPS and MOS:TMCAPS--> is a [[fighting game]] developed and published by [[Nintendo]] for the [[Nintendo Switch]], which released on June 16, 2017. The game differentiates itself from standard fighting games with its unconventional fighting system where every playable character fights with long range attacks, and up to four players can choose a fighter and battle using a variety of extendable, customizable arms to knock out opponents in a three-dimensional arena. By July 2018, the game had sold over two million copies worldwide, making it one of the [[List of best-selling Nintendo Switch video games|best-selling games on the Switch]].\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Arms Gameplay Match.jpg|left|thumb|A match of ''ARMS'' being played between Spring Man and Ribbon Girl.]]\n''Arms'' is a 3D fighting sports game in which up to four players can control one of a variety of fighters, with the player able to perform basic fighting actions using extendable arms such as punching, throwing, blocking, and dodging.<ref name=\"Poly\">{{cite web|last=Frank|first=Allegra|date=January 12, 2017|url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/1/12/14260222/arms-nintendo-switch|title=Arms is a fantasy fighter for Nintendo Switch|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=January 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=January 13, 2017|url=https://www.polygon.com/nintendo-switch/2017/1/13/14263462/nintendo-switch-arms-fighting|title=Arms is the competitive, motion controlled fighting game coming to Nintendo Switch|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=January 13, 2017}}</ref> ''Arms'' features fifteen playable fighters, with five of them being released as [[downloadable content]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gilyadov|first=Alex|date=June 15, 2017|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/06/15/e3-2017-first-arms-dlc-character-revealed|title=E3 2017: First Arms DLC Character Revealed|website=[[IGN]]|accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref> Each fighter starts with three unique Arms that can be selected in battle, but the use of all other fighters' Arms can be unlocked in the Get Arms mode. All fighters also have unique attributes in combat.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ramos|first=Jeff|date=June 16, 2017|url=https://www.polygon.com/arms-guide/2017/6/16/15765392/arms-nintendo-switch-best-character|title=How to choose the best character in Arms|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref> When the attack meter is fully charged, players are able to unleash a high-damage \"rush attack\" against their opponents. Players can also charge their attacks to temporarily increase damage and utilize elemental effects.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nunneley|first=Stephany|date=June 8, 2017|url=https://www.vg247.com/2017/06/08/arms-heres-six-tips-to-help-you-dominate-your-opponents/|title=Arms \u2013 here are six tips to help you dominate opponents|website=[[VG247]]|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref> Each character has a different set of abilities and unique Arms for different strategies. Players are able to use the system's [[Joy-Con]] motion controls or standard button inputs with controllers such as the Pro Controller to operate each Arm individually. Players are also able to customize their Arm load outs, with each Arm being able to be selected independently. Every Arm is different with elemental attributes and varying weights that affect gameplay. Up to four players are able to play in a single match, either in a three or four-way free-for-all, or in a two-on-two mode in which teammates are tethered together.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://arms.nintendo.com/battle/|title=Battle Modes - ARMS for Nintendo|website=[[Nintendo]]|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Karassik|first=Neila|date=June 12, 2017|url=http://www.space.ca/arms-nintendo-switch-game-review/|title=Nintendo Switch's ARMS Is A Knockout - And That's No Stretch|website=Space}}</ref>\n\nBesides the standard fighting mode, ''Arms'' features multiple other modes: Versus, Grand Prix, and a variety of Battle modes. In Grand Prix, players take on a set of 10 matches against computer-controlled fighters to win the championship belt. Battle mode consists of [[volleyball]] and [[basketball]] modes, a target breaking mode, and a survival mode.<ref name=\":0\"/> Players can also play online in a party match lobby with up to 20 players, or in one-on-one ranked matches.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stark|first=Chelsea|date=May 17, 2017|url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/5/17/15655898/arms-nintendo-switch-game-modes|title=Arms' new game modes are a weird take on classic sports|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=June 6, 2017}}</ref> ''Arms'' featured ten playable fighters at launch, with five additional fighters added via post-release updates.<ref>{{cite web |last=Frank |first=Allegra |date=August 22, 2017 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/8/22/16182734/arms-free-demo-playable-characters-lola-pop-trailer |title=Arms\u2019 new fighter is a human balloon animal |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Romano |first=Sal |date=November 15, 2017 |url=https://gematsu.com/2017/11/arms-version-4-0-update-now-available-adds-new-fighter-misango |title=Arms version 4.0 update now available, adds new fighter Misango |website=Gematsu |accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\nThe game was developed by Nintendo's [[Entertainment Planning & Development]] division, produced by Kosuke Yabuki.<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|title=ARMS Dev. Talk - ft. Mr. Yabuki|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aofi13XiVXA|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> In the beginning, the game began as a wish to see if a behind-the-camera perspective could work in a fighting game.<ref name=\":1\" /> To make this idea work, the main feature of extendable arms was implemented, with Yabuki stating \"Let's talk about a game I know about very well - Mario Kart. Something appears in the distance and you steer in relation to that - that's the basic structure of the game,\" in reference to ''[[Mario Kart]]'' and how its gameplay helped influence ''Arms''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-03-22-early-arms-prototypes-showcase-cut-bowling-mini-game|title=Early prototype of Arms revealed, including a cut bowling mini-game|last=Reynolds|first=Matthew|date=2018-03-22|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref>\n\nEarly on, the idea of featuring staple Nintendo characters such as [[Link (The Legend of Zelda)|Link]] and [[Mario]] was considered. However, the aesthetic of the game, especially with the concept of extendable arms, clashed with them, and it was eventually decided that a new cast of characters be created.<ref name=\"VBeat\">{{cite web |last=Webster |first=Andrew |date=June 6, 2017 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/6/6/15746164/nintendo-switch-arms-character-design-interview |title=How Nintendo Created Its Wild New Cast of Fighters for Switch Game Arms |website=[[The Verge]] |accessdate=June 8, 2017}}</ref> The possibility of adding characters from ''[[Punch-Out!!]]'' was also considered but the team was concerned about alienating fans of that franchise and potentially confusing new players.<ref>{{cite web |last=McWhertor |first=Michael |date=March 26, 2018 |url=https://www.polygon.com/interviews/2018/3/26/17164492/arms-nintendo-switch-interview-kosuke-yabuki |title=Arms director Kosuke Yabuki on the past and future of the Switch fighting game |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCharacter designs started with the arms first with the team working backwards to decide what type of character would possess it, for instance the character of Helix, started with the idea of a fighter whose arms were [[DNA]] strands, although the team initially did not know much else about him. Most fighters were designed to fill a gameplay need, although there are some exceptions where a design came first.<ref name=\"VBeat\" /> An early concept for the game had the characters using external devices to punch their opponents; however, this was later dropped in favor of the characters extending their actual arms.<ref name=\"GInformer\">{{cite web |last=Hillard |first=Kyle |date=June 7, 2017 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2017/06/02/-arms-creators-on-twintelles-popularity-and-the-strange-lore-of-the-games-world-luffy-one-piece.aspx |title=Arms' Creators On Twintelle's Popularity And The Strange Lore Of The Game's World |website=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=June 8, 2017}}</ref> Art director Masaaki Ishikawa said that the game's art style was largely influenced by ''[[Dragon Ball]]'' and ''[[Akira (manga)|Akira]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Simon |last2=Davison |first2=John |date=June 14, 2017 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/glixel/features/because-nintendo-arms-producer-explains-why-fighters-have-stretchy-arms-w487949 |title='Because Nintendo': 'Arms' Producer Explains Why Fighters Have Stretchy Arms |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=October 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe game was announced at the Nintendo Switch Presentation on January 12, 2017, and was released worldwide on June 16, 2017.<ref name=Poly/><ref>{{cite web |last=Goldfarb |first=Andrew |date=April 12, 2017 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/04/12/arms-release-date-announced-for-nintendo-switch |title=Splatoon 2 Release Date, Amiibo Set Announced |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=April 12, 2017}}</ref> Prior to the game's release, a multiplayer [[Game demo|demo]] known as the \"''Arms'' Global Testpunch\" was made available for download on the [[Nintendo eShop]], with players being able to test the online gameplay during twelve separate hour-long sessions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://arms.nintendo.com/#global-testpunch |title=ARMS for the Nintendo Switch\u2122 home gaming system \u2013 Official Site |website=[[Nintendo]] |accessdate=May 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Roberts |first=David |date=May 17, 2017 |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/try-out-nintendos-upcoming-switch-fighter-arms-with-two-global-testpunch-events-starting-may-26/ |title=Try out Nintendo's upcoming Switch fighter Arms with two Global Testpunch events, starting May 26 |website=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=May 18, 2017}}</ref> \n\nIrregular post-release updates were released featuring new playable characters, stages, and arms.<ref>{{cite web |author=Nintendo |date=May 17, 2017 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hY2_Xu3f8Bc |title=ARMS Direct 5.17.2017 |website=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=May 18, 2017}}</ref> These free releases of additional content followed ''[[Splatoon]]''{{'s}} update model,<ref>{{Cite web |last=McCarthy |first=Caty |date=May 17, 2017 |url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/arms-unveils-new-characters-modes-global-testpunch-nintendo-direct |title=Arms Unveils New Characters, Modes, a Global Testpunch, and More in Latest Nintendo Direct |website=[[USGamer]] |accessdate=May 18, 2017}}</ref> while the Testpunch demo was also available for use multiple times. The game received new characters and stages by way of downloadable content until December 2017, when Nintendo announced that they would no longer be adding new content to the game other than [[Balance (game design)|balance]] updates.<ref>{{cite web |author=Nintendo |date=December 22, 2017 |url=https://topics.nintendo.co.jp/c/article/67b3f436-e451-11e7-8cda-063b7ac45a6d.html |title=\"Theoretically strongest\" fighter entry! \"ARMS\" Ver. 5 update |website=[[Nintendo]] |accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/nintendos-arms-gets-its-last-new-character-1821529481/|title=Nintendo's Arms Gets Its Last New Character|date=22 December 2017|accessdate=25 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=McWhertor |first=Michael |date=October 5, 2017 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/01/25/nintendo-has-no-plans-for-additional-arms-content |title=NINTENDO HAS 'NO PLANS' FOR ADDITIONAL ARMS CONTENT |website=IGN |accessdate=January 25, 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn May 2018, a demo of the game was released on the eShop for a limited time only. Unlike the Testpunch events, this demo only featured offline modes of single-player and local multiplayer with a limited selection of characters and Arms to choose from.<ref>{{cite web|title=ARMS demo now available|url=https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/arms-demo-now-available|website=Nintendo|accessdate=May 12, 2018|date=May 10, 2018}}</ref> \n\nA temporary Free Game Trial was made available for free to Nintendo Switch Online members from March 26th to April 6th, 2020. This free trial allowed players to experience the entirety of the game's features and modes for the alloted time.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = 77/100<ref name=Metacritic>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/switch/arms |title=ARMS for Switch Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=June 7, 2017}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 7/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Carter |first=Chris |date=June 16, 2017 |url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-arms-438597.phtml |title=Review: Arms |website=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=June 17, 2017}}</ref>\n| Edge = 9/10<ref name=\"Edge\" />\n| EGM = 8.5/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Schaeffer |first=Emma |date=June 7, 2017 |url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/arms-review/|title=Arms Review |website=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGMNow]] |accessdate=June 17, 2017}}</ref>\n| Fam = 33/40<ref name=Fam>{{cite web |last=Romano |first=Sal |date=June 6, 2017 |url=https://gematsu.com/2017/06/famitsu-review-scores-issue-1488 |title=Famitsu Review Scores: Issue 1488 |website=Gematsu |accessdate=June 8, 2017}}</ref>\n| GI = 8.25/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Shea |first=Brian |date=June 7, 2017 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/arms/b/switch/archive/2017/06/07/arms-game-informer-review.aspx |title=Arms Review - Punching Up |website=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=June 17, 2017}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 7/10<ref name=\"GameSpot review\">{{cite web |last=Plagge |first=Kallie |date=June 7, 2017 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/arms-review/1900-6416696/ |title=Arms Review |website=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Schilling |first=Chris |date=June 7, 2017 |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/arms-review/ |title=Arms review: 'An invigorating blend of graceful movement and slapstick violence' |website=[[GamesRadar]]}}</ref>\n| IGN = 8/10<ref name=\"IGN review\">{{cite web |last=Graeber |first=Brendan |date=June 7, 2017 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/06/07/arms-review |title=Arms Review |website=[[IGN]]}}</ref>\n| NLife = {{Rating|9|10}}<ref>{{cite web |last=McFerran |first=Damien |date=June 16, 2017 |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/nintendo-switch/arms |title=Review: Arms (Switch) |website=[[Nintendo Life]] |accessdate=June 17, 2017}}</ref>\n| NWR = 8/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Ronaghan |first=Neal |date=June 7, 2017 |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/44768/arms-switch-review |title=Arms (Switch) Review |website=Nintendo World Report |accessdate=June 17, 2017}}</ref>\n| Poly = 8/10<ref name=\"Polygon review\">{{cite web |last=McWhertor |first=Michael |date=June 7, 2017 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/6/7/15751828/arms-review-nintendo-switch |title=Arms review |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''Hardcore Gamer''\n| rev1Score = 4.5/5<ref>{{cite web |last=Swalley |first=Kirstin |date=June 7, 2017|url=https://www.hardcoregamer.com/2017/06/07/review-arms/259968/|title=Review: ARMS|work=Hardcore Gamer |accessdate=July 20, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAt its announcement, ''Arms'' was compared by critics to the boxing minigame from ''[[Wii Sports]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hardawar |first=Devindra |date=January 12, 2017 |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/01/12/arms-brings-shooter-esque-boxing-to-the-nintendo-switch/ |title='Arms' brings shooter-esque boxing to the Nintendo Switch |website=[[Engadget]] |accessdate=January 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Prell |first=Sam |date=January 12, 2017 |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/switch-game-arms-is-like-boxing-if-boxing-starred-anime-characters-with-slinkies-for-arms/ |title=Switch game Arms is like boxing, if boxing starred anime characters with Slinkies for... arms |website=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=January 13, 2017}}</ref> Jack Sheperd of ''[[The Independent]]'' stated after playing it at a Switch hands-on event that it was one of the \"most impressive\" games on display.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shepherd |first=Jack |date=January 16, 2017 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/gaming/nintendo-switch-hands-on-review-zelda-mario-1-2-switch-arms-breath-of-wind-a7530396.html |title=Nintendo Switch hands-on review: Brilliant device, lacklustre line-up |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=February 22, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]'' compared ''Arms'' with other Nintendo titles and thought that \"''Arms'' is to the fighting game what ''[[Splatoon]]'' is to the online shooter or ''[[Mario Kart]]'' to the [[Racing video game|driving game]]\".<ref name=\"Edge\">{{cite magazine |author=Edge staff |date=April 27, 2017 |url=https://www.pressreader.com/australia/edge/20170427/281483571275804 |title=The art of fighting without fighting? Show me some of it |magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] |accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe game received \"generally favorable\" reviews, according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name=Metacritic /> Brandon Graeber from [[IGN]] praised the game's complexity and addictive nature, but noted the game's lack of content at launch.<ref name=\"IGN review\"/> Michael McWhertor from ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' applauded the game's concept, which he described as creative, and that the game reminded him of the ''[[Punch-Out!!]]'' series, stating that ''Arms'' could become Nintendo's next big franchise.<ref name=\"Polygon review\"/> Kallie Plagge from [[GameSpot]] praised the character roster, but criticized the game's steep [[learning curve]].<ref name=\"GameSpot review\"/>\n\nMultiple publications listed the game as one of the best of 2017.<ref>{{cite web |author=Eurogamer staff |date=December 30, 2017 |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-12-30-eurogamers-top-50-games-of-2017-10-1 |title=Eurogamer's Top 50 Games of 2017: 10-1 |website=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=EGM staff |date=December 27, 2017 |url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/features/egms-best-of-2017-part-one-25-21/ |title=EGM's Best of 2017: Part One: #25 ~ #21 |website=EGMNow |accessdate=January 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180114191051/http://www.egmnow.com/articles/features/egms-best-of-2017-part-one-25-21/ |archive-date=January 14, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Polygon staff |date=December 18, 2017 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2017-best-games/2017/12/18/16781674/best-video-games-2017-top-50-mario-pubg-zelda |title=The 50 best games of 2017 |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref> In ''[[Game Informer]]''{{'}}s Reader's Choice Best of 2017 Awards, the game placed third for \"Best Fighting Game\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Cork |first=Jeff |date=January 4, 2018 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2018/01/04/reader-s-choice-best-of-2017-awards.aspx?PostPageIndex=2 |title=Reader's Choice Best Of 2017 Awards (Page 2) |website=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref> It was also nominated for the same category in [[IGN]]'s Best of 2017 Awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/wikis/best-of-2017-awards/Best_Fighting_Game |title=Best of 2017 Awards: Best Fighting Game |website=[[IGN]] |date=December 20, 2017 |accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref> The game has seen a small, but dedicated [[esports]] scene across multiple regions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://compete.kotaku.com/a-pocket-of-passionate-players-is-the-only-thing-keepin-1821777320|title=A Pocket Of Passionate Players Is The Only Thing Keeping Competitive ARMS Alive|website=Compete|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\n===Sales===\n''Arms'' debuted at number two on the UK sales charts, behind ''[[Horizon Zero Dawn]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Dayus |first=Oscar |date=June 19, 2017 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/top-10-uk-sales-chart-horizon-zero-dawn-beats-swit/1100-6451022/ |title=Top 10 UK Sales Chart: Horizon Zero Dawn Beats Switch's Arms To No.1 |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=June 19, 2017}}</ref> It was number two in Australia, behind the same game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.igea.net/2017/06/top-10-games-for-the-week-ended-18-june-2017/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=July 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729180245/http://www.igea.net/2017/06/top-10-games-for-the-week-ended-18-june-2017/ |archive-date=July 29, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It sold 100,652 physical copies during its first week of release in Japan, and debuted at number one on the all-format sales charts.<ref>{{cite web |last=Romano |first=Sal |date=June 21, 2017 |url=http://gematsu.com/2017/06/media-create-sales-61217-61817 |title=Media Create Sales: 6/12/17 \u2013 6/18/17 |publisher=Gematsu |accessdate=June 23, 2017}}</ref> By September 30, 2018, the game had sold over 2.1 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/finance/software/index.html|title=IR Information : Sales Data - Top Selling Title Sales Units|website=Nintendo Co., Ltd.|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203005532/https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/finance/software/index.html|archive-date=2018-12-03|access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\" | 2017\n| rowspan=\"1\" | [[Game Critics Awards]]\n| Best Fighting Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamecriticsawards.com/nominees.html |title=Game Critics Awards: Best of E3 2017 (2017 Nominees) |website=[[Game Critics Awards]] |accessdate=December 31, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | [[Golden Joystick Awards]]\n| Nintendo Game of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Gaito |first=Eri |date=November 13, 2017 |url=https://www.bestinslot.co/golden-joystick-awards-2017-nominees/ |title=Golden Joystick Awards 2017 Nominees |website=Best in Slot |accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Weber |first=Rachel |date=November 17, 2017 |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/the-legend-of-zelda-breath-of-the-wild-scores-big-at-the-35th-golden-joystick-awards-presented-with-omen-by-hp/ |title=The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild scores big at the 35th Golden Joystick Awards presented with OMEN by HP |website=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | [[The Game Awards 2017]]\n| Best Fighting Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Makuch |first=Eddie |date=December 8, 2017 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-game-awards-2017-winners-headlined-by-zelda-br/1100-6455467/ |title=The Game Awards 2017 Winners Headlined By Zelda: Breath Of The Wild's Game Of The Year |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\" | 2018\n| rowspan=\"1\" | New York Game Awards\n| Central Park Children's Zoo Award for Best Kids Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Whitney |first=Kayla |date=January 25, 2018 |url=https://www.axs.com/complete-list-of-winners-of-the-new-york-game-awards-2018-127527 |title=Complete list of winners of the New York Game Awards 2018 |website=[[AXS (company)|AXS]] |accessdate=January 27, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | [[D.I.C.E. Awards]]\n| Fighting Game of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Makuch |first=Eddie |date=January 14, 2018 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/game-of-the-year-nominees-announced-for-dice-award/1100-6456107/ |title=Game Of The Year Nominees Announced For DICE Awards |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=January 17, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | [[NAVGTR Awards]]\n| Game, Original Fighting\n| {{Won}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |url=http://navgtr.org/archives/3351/ |title=Nominee List for 2017 |website=[[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]] |date=February 9, 2018 |accessdate=February 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180215172210/http://navgtr.org/archives/3351/ |archive-date=February 15, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://navgtr.org/archives/3365/ |title=Horizon wins 7; Mario GOTY |website=[[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]] |date=March 13, 2018 |accessdate=March 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180314070824/http://navgtr.org/archives/3365/ |archive-date=March 14, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Legacy==\nA graphic novel by [[Dark Horse Comics]] based on ''Arms'' is under production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2017/12/19/arms-comic-announced-written-by-ian-flynn.aspx|title=ARMS Comic Announced, Written By Ian Flynn|last=Khan|first=Imran|website=Game Informer|language=en|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/53020/arms-graphic-novel-status-update|title=ARMS Graphic Novel Status Update|last=Berube|first=Justin|website=Nintendo World Report|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> Spring Man appears as an Assist Trophy in the 2018 crossover [[fighting game]] ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]'', as well as an upcoming fighter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20181101005675/en/Super-Smash-Bros.-Ultimate-Nintendo-Direct-Unleashes|title=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Nintendo Direct Unleashes New Details|date=2018-11-01|website=www.businesswire.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref><ref>https://www.ign.com/articles/super-smash-bros-ultimates-next-dlc-character-will-be-from-arms</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{officialwebsite|https://web.archive.org/web/20190405165149/https://arms.nintendo.com/}} (archived)\n\n{{Portal bar|Video games}}\n\n[[Category:2017 video games]]\n[[Category:3D fighting games]]\n[[Category:Fighting games used at the Evolution Championship Series tournament]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Entertainment Planning & Development games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch eShop games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch-only games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Wii U games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female antagonists]]\n[[Category:Versus fighting games]]\n[[Category:Split-screen multiplayer games]]\n", "name_user": "Dissident93", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arms_(video_game)"}
{"title_page": "Toby Stephens", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Toby Stephens\n| image = Toby Stephens by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption = Stephens at WonderCon 2018\n| imagesize = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1969|4|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Fitzrovia]], [[London]], England\n| nationality = British\n| occupation = Actor\n| years_active = 1992\u2013present\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Anna-Louise Plowman]]|2001}}\n| children = 3\n| parents=[[Robert Stephens|Sir Robert Stephens]]<br>[[Maggie Smith|Dame Maggie Smith]]\n| relatives=[[Chris Larkin]] <small>(brother)</small>\n}}\n'''Toby Stephens''' (born 21 April 1969) is an English stage, television, radio and film actor who has appeared in films in both the UK and US as well as in [[Bollywood|India]]. He is known for the roles of [[Bond villain]] Gustav Graves in the 2002 [[James Bond]] film ''[[Die Another Day]]'' (for which he was nominated for the [[Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actor]]), Edward Fairfax Rochester in a BBC television adaptation of ''[[Jane Eyre (2006 miniseries)|Jane Eyre]]'' and in his role as [[Captain Flint]] in the [[Starz (TV channel)|Starz]] television series ''[[Black Sails (TV series)|Black Sails]]''. Stephens is a lead in the [[Netflix]] science fiction series [[Lost in Space (2018 TV series)|''Lost in Space'']], which began streaming in 2018.\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Seaford College.jpg|thumb|left|230px|Seaford College]]\nStephens, the younger son of actors Dame [[Maggie Smith]] and Sir [[Robert Stephens]], was born at the [[Middlesex Hospital]] in [[Fitzrovia]], London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=pyQ0p3El8c6jc1Gd5Nrytw&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=13 January 2018|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> He was educated at Aldro School and [[Seaford College]], which he hated.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/11721542/Dame-Maggie-Smiths-son-Stop-calling-me-posh.html |title=Dame Maggie Smith's son: 'Stop calling me posh' |author=Anita Singh |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=7 July 2015 |accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/5355982/Toby-Stephens-Being-born-into-the-theatre-was-a-mixed-blessing.html |title=Toby Stephens: Being born into the theatre was a mixed blessing |author=Tim Walker |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=21 May 2009 |accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> He then trained at the [[London Academy of Music and Dramatic Art]] (LAMDA).<ref>{{cite web |title=2011 : APPEARANCES |date=3 February 2014 |url=http://toby-stephens.tumblr.com/post/75484260498/2011-appearances |publisher=toby-stephens.tumblr.com |accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nStephens began his film career with the role of Othello in 1992, in [[Sally Potter]]'s ''[[Orlando (film)|Orlando]]''. He has since made regular appearances on television (including in ''[[The Camomile Lawn (TV serial)|The Camomile Lawn]]'', 1992) and on stage.\n\nHe played the title role in a [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] production of ''[[Coriolanus (play)|Coriolanus]]'' shortly after graduation from LAMDA; that same season he played Claudio in ''[[Measure for Measure]]'' for the RSC. He also played [[Stanley Kowalski]] in a [[West End theatre|West End]] production of [[Tennessee Williams]]' ''[[A Streetcar Named Desire (play)|A Streetcar Named Desire]]'', and ''[[Hamlet]]'' in 2004. He has appeared on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in ''Ring Round the Moon''. He played the lead in the film ''[[Photographing Fairies]]'' and played Orsino in [[Trevor Nunn]]'s [[Twelfth Night (1996 film)|1996 film adaptation]] of [[William Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Twelfth Night]]''. In 2002 he took on the role of Gustav Graves in the [[James Bond]] film ''[[Die Another Day]]''. Aged 33 at the time of film's release, he remains the youngest actor to have played a [[Bond villain]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Larushka |last=Ivan-Zadeh |title=Black Sails actor Toby Stephens: Most British scripts you get sent are just awful |date=20 March 2014 |url=http://metro.co.uk/2014/03/20/black-sails-actor-toby-stephens-most-british-scripts-you-get-sent-are-just-awful-4656483/ |publisher=Metro |accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005 he played the role of a [[British Army]] captain in the Indian film, ''[[Mangal Pandey: The Rising|The Rising: Ballad of Mangal Pandey]]'', portraying events in the [[Indian rebellion of 1857]]. The following year he returned to India to play a renegade [[British East India Company]] officer in ''[[Sharpe's Challenge]]''. In late 2006 he starred as Edward Rochester in the  highly acclaimed [[BBC]] television adaptation of ''[[Jane Eyre (2006 miniseries)|Jane Eyre]]'' (broadcast in the United States on [[PBS]] in early 2007) and ''The Wild West'' in February 2007 for the [[BBC]] in which he played [[General George Armstrong Custer]] in ''[[Custer's Last Stand]]''.\n\nDuring mid-2007, Stephens played the role of Jerry in a revival of [[Harold Pinter]]'s ''[[Betrayal (play)|Betrayal]]'' under the direction of [[Roger Michell]]. Later that year, Stephens also starred as Horner in [[Jonathan Kent (director)|Jonathan Kent]]'s revival of [[William Wycherley]]'s ''[[The Country Wife]]''. The play was the inaugural production of the Theatre Royal Haymarket Company, which in addition to Stephens includes the actors/actresses [[Eileen Atkins]], [[Patricia Hodge]], [[David Haig]] and [[Ruthie Henshall]]. Various members of the company are expected to star in upcoming productions at the [[Haymarket Theatre]] with various artistic directors. The formation of the company is considered by many London theatre critics to be a bold move for West End theatre.<ref>David Benedict, \"Theatre Royal Haymarket Gambles\", ''Variety,'' 23 July 2007, online edition. [https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117968953.html?categoryid=2244&cs=1&query=royal+gamble+haymarket]</ref>\n\n[[File:Toby Stephens (retouched).jpg|thumb|right|220px|Toby Stephens in 2014.]]\nIn February 2008, the [[Fox Broadcasting Company]] gave the go-ahead to cast Stephens as the lead in a potential one hour, prime time US television show, ''Inseparable'', to be produced by [[Shaun Cassidy]]. Billed as a modern [[Jekyll and Hyde]] story, the show was to feature a partially paralysed forensic psychologist whose other personality is a charming criminal. Stephens' casting was highly unusual, because Fox had not yet approved a script nor purchased a pilot for the show. However, in mid-May 2008, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' announced that \"[b]y the time the network picked up the pilot . . . [the producers'] hold on Stephens had expired . . . .\"<ref>Nellie Andreeva, \"Busy Pre-upfront Weekend\", ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', 10 May 2008, updated 11 May 2008, Online edition. [https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i5e732e045deaaba38a97b3781febda02]</ref><ref>[http://www.zap2it.com/tv/news/zap-fox200909schedulebuzz,0,3485063.story \"Pilot Buzz\", ''zap2it'', 12 May 2008]</ref>\n\nIn May 2008, Stephens performed the role of [[James Bond]] in a [[BBC Radio 4]] production of [[Ian Fleming]]'s ''[[Dr. No (novel)|Dr. No]]'', as part of the centenary celebration of Fleming's birth. The production was reportedly the first BBC radio dramatisation of the novel though ''Moonraker'' was on South African radio in 1956, with [[Bob Holness]] providing the voice of Bond.<ref>{{ cite web | url=http://www.ukgameshows.com/ukgs/Bob_Holness | title=Bob Holness on Game Shows | accessdate=14 September 2007 }}</ref> He has since appeared in a number of adaptations of other James Bond novels.\n\nAlso in May 2008, Stock-pot Productions announced that Stephens will have the lead role in a feature-length film entitled ''Fly Me'', co-starring [[Tim McInnerny]].<ref>[http://www.stockpotproductions.co.uk/ Stock-pot Productions Limited, Blog, 27 May 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060421050551/http://www.stockpotproductions.co.uk/ |date=21 April 2006 }}</ref> Stock-pot was also the producer of ''One Day'', a short 2006 film shown at international film festivals, in which Stephens played a small part as the boss of McInnerny's character.\n\nOn 5 October 2008, Stephens appeared onstage at the [[London Palladium]] as part of a benefit entitled \"The Story of [[James Bond]], A Tribute to [[Ian Fleming]].\" The event, organised by Fleming's niece, [[Lucy Fleming]], featured music from various James Bond films and Bond film stars reading from Fleming's Bond novels. Stephens took the part of James Bond himself in the readings.\n\nIn early December 2008, Stephens read from ''Coda'', the last book written by his good friend [[Simon Gray]], for [[BBC Radio 4]]. The excerpts from which Stephens read included Gray's description of his participation as godfather at the christening of Stephens' son Eli.\n\nEarly in 2009, Stephens appeared as Prince John in season 3 of the [[BBC]] series ''[[Robin Hood (2006 TV series)|Robin Hood]]''. The series also aired on [[BBC America]] in the United States. Stephens' more recent television appearances include two episodes of a six-part television series, ''[[Strike Back (TV series)|Strike Back]]'', based on the novel by [[Chris Ryan]].<ref>Dan French, \"Richard Armitage for Sky1's 'Strike Back'\", \"Digital Spy\", 24 August 2009 [http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a173500/richard-armitage-for-sky1s-strike-back.html]</ref> The series aired in May 2010.\n\nIn mid-2009, Stephens returned to the London stage in the [[Donmar Warehouse]] production of [[Ibsen]]'s ''[[A Doll's House]]'' alongside [[Gillian Anderson]] and [[Christopher Eccleston]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Charles |last=Spencer |title=A Doll's House, at the Donmar Warehouse \u2013 review |date=20 May 2009 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/charles-spencer/5354252/A-Dolls-House-at-the-Donmar-Warehouse-review.html |publisher=The Telegraph |accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he starred in the made-for-television film, ''The Blue Geranium,'' a further sequel to the television series and films based on [[Agatha Christie]]'s [[Miss Marple]] character.<ref>\"Julia McKenzie returns as the fictional sleuth Miss Marple, in her seventh film The Blue Geranium for ITV1\", ITV.com, 21 January 2010 {{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/presscentre/pressreleases/programmepressreleases/juliamckenziereturnsasthefictionalsleuthmissmarpleinherseventhfilmthebluegeraniumforitv1/default.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100131132737/http://www.itv.com/presscentre/pressreleases/programmepressreleases/juliamckenziereturnsasthefictionalsleuthmissmarpleinherseventhfilmthebluegeraniumforitv1/default.html |archivedate=31 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The show was broadcast in the US on [[PBS]] in June 2010. Stephens also recently starred as a highly self-centred detective opposite [[Lucy Punch]] in a three-part comedy television series for [[BBC Two]] entitled ''[[Vexed]]''.<ref>Katherine Rushton, \"Greenlit Gets First BBC Order with Cop Comedy\", \"Broadcast\", 23 July 2009 [http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/greenlit-gets-first-bbc-order-with-cop-comedy/5003838.article]</ref>\n\nStephens took on a small supporting role in a short film, ''The Lost Explorer,'' the directorial debut of photographer [[Tim Walker]]. The film is based on a short story by author [[Patrick McGrath (novelist)|Patrick McGrath]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dazedmagonline.com/dazedmag/201005?pg=27#pg27|title=Sam Elliott Connor, \"The Lost Explorer,\" \"Dazed & Confused,\" May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304154314/http://www.dazedmagonline.com/dazedmag/201005?pg=27#pg27|archivedate=4 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nMeantime, on the London stage in the spring of 2010, Stephens received outstanding reviews for his performance as Henry in a revival of [[Tom Stoppard]]'s ''[[The Real Thing (play)|The Real Thing]]'', directed by [[Anna Mackmin]] at the [[The Old Vic|Old Vic Theatre]] in London.<ref>Leo Benedictus, \"What to say about...The Real Thing\", \"The Guardian\", 23 April 2010 [https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2010/apr/23/the-real-thing-tom-stoppard-reviews]</ref> Of debuting at the Old Vic, where his parents performed as part of [[Laurence Olivier]]'s [[Royal National Theatre]] Company, Stephens said: \"It's quite moving for me to do something there. It means it has an added fascination. It was an historic place but I never saw anything when [my parents] were there, which is really sad, because I was just born. I'm a huge admirer of Stoppard's work.\"<ref>Louise Jury, \"Toby's emotional debut for classic Stoppard play\", ''[[London Evening Standard]]'', 7 December 2009. {{cite web |url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23780593-tobys-emotional-debut-for-classic-stoppard-play.do |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213011210/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23780593-tobys-emotional-debut-for-classic-stoppard-play.do |archivedate=13 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Stephens appeared as [[Georges Danton]] in ''[[Danton's Death]]''. The play was another debut for Stephens, this time at London's [[Royal National Theatre]].<ref>\"Slumdog's Danny Boyle Returns to the Stage as Frankenstein,\" Theatre News, ''[[London Evening Standard]]'', 21 January 2010. [https://www.londontheatre.co.uk/theatre-news/news/national-theatre-announce-future-productions-2010]</ref><ref>Terri Paddock, \"20 Questions with... Toby Stephens,\" ''whatsonstage.com'' 19 November 2001. {{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/interviews/theatre/london/E8821005841402/20+Questions+With...Toby+Stephens.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100121155048/http://www.whatsonstage.com/interviews/theatre/london/E8821005841402/20+Questions+With...Toby+Stephens.html |archivedate=21 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOver the years, Stephens has continued to prolifically narrate audiobooks and perform in broadcast radio dramas; in the last three years, he has averaged four or five such performances per year. In January 2011, Stephens joined other stars in narrating portions of the [[King James Version]] of the Bible for [[BBC Radio 4]] as part of a celebration of the 400th anniversary of the Bible's publication. Stephens performed the role of [[Raymond Chandler]]'s [[Philip Marlowe]] in a radio serial, which debuted in February 2011. Stephens narrated another audiobook, ''Paul Temple and the Geneva Mystery,'' released in February 2011.\n\nIn 2016, he was cast as former British Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] in the film ''[[The Journey (2016 film)|The Journey]]'' which featured [[Timothy Spall]] as firebrand preacher and eventual Northern Ireland First Minister Ian Paisley with [[Colm Meaney]] playing Martin McGuinness. John Hurt also starred.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/festivals/john-hurt-toby-stephens-freddy-highmore-the-journey-1201589815/|title=Toronto: John Hurt, Toby Stephens, Freddie Highmore Join \u2018The Journey\u2019|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=2015-09-10|work=Variety|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, he appears as John Robinson in ''[[Lost in Space (2018 TV series)|Lost in Space]]'', the [[Netflix]] remake of the [[Lost in Space|1965 TV series]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|title=Toby Stephens To Topline 'Lost in Space' Netflix Remake, Maxwell Jenkins To Co-Star|url=https://deadline.com/2016/09/toby-stephens-to-topline-lost-in-space-netflix-remake-maxwell-jenkins-co-stars-1201823340/|website=deadline.com|accessdate=20 September 2016|date=2016-09-20}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nStephens and [[New Zealand]] actress [[Anna-Louise Plowman]] were married in 2001. Their first child, son Eli Alistair, was born in May 2007.<ref>{{Citation | first = Mark | last = Lawson | title = Prodigal Son | newspaper = The Guardian | date = 31 May 2007 | edition = online | url = http://arts.guardian.co.uk/theatre/drama/story/0,,2091828,00.html}}.</ref> The renowned British playwright [[Simon Gray]] (who penned ''Japes'', a stage play, and ''Missing Dates'', a radio drama, both of which starred Stephens), was reported to be Eli's godfather.<ref>Janice Turner, [http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/article3801820.ece \"Simon Gray Has Lung Cancer But Won't Stop Smoking\"], ''The Times'', 24 April 2008, Online edition.</ref> Their daughters, Tallulah and Kura, were born in May 2009<ref>Tim Walker, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/5355982/Toby-Stephens-Being-born-into-the-theatre-was-a-mixed-blessing.html \"Toby Stephens: Being born into the theatre was a mixed blessing],\" ''The Daily Telegraph'', 21 May 2009, Online edition.</ref> and in September 2010, respectively.\n\nPlowman and Stephens performed together as Sibyl and Elyot in [[Jonathan Kent (director)|Jonathan Kent]]'s revival of ''[[Private Lives]]'' for the 2012 [[Chichester Festival Theatre|Chichester Festival]],<ref>{{cite news | title = Private Lives \u2013 Minerva, Chichester | author = [[Michael Billington (critic)|Michael Billington]] | newspaper = [[The Guardian]] | date = 30 September 2012 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2012/sep/30/private-lives-review }}</ref> reprised at the [[Gielgud Theatre]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite news | title= It\u2019s odd kissing Toby Stephens with his wife in the cast, says Private Lives actress Anna Chancellor  | url = https://www.standard.co.uk/news/its-odd-kissing-toby-stephens-with-his-wife-in-the-cast-says-private-lives-actress-anna-chancellor-8687539.html | authors = Louise Jury and Josh Pettitt | date = 4 July 2013 | newspaper = [[Evening Standard]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Theatre review: Private Lives | newspaper = [[The Independent]] | author = Paul Taylor | date = 4 July 2013 | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/reviews/theatre-review-private-lives--jonathan-kents-rendition-of-cowards-masterpiece-is-the-best-in-a-decade-8687498.html}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year || Title || Role || Director || Notes\n|-\n| 1992 || ''[[Orlando (film)|Orlando]]'' || [[Othello]] || [[Sally Potter]] || Written by [[Sally Potter]], based on the novel ''Orlando'' by [[Virginia Woolf]]\n|-\n| 1996 || ''[[Twelfth Night (1996 film)|Twelfth Night]]'' || Duke Orsino || [[Trevor Nunn]] || Based on the [[Shakespeare]] play ''[[Twelfth Night]]''\n|-\n| 1997 || ''[[Photographing Fairies]]'' || Charles Castle || [[Nick Willing]] || Based on the book by [[Steve Szilagyi]]\n|-\n| 1998 || ''Cousin Bette'' || Victorin Hulot || [[Des McAnuff]] || Based on the book ''[[Cousin Bette]]'' by [[Honor\u00e9 de Balzac]]\n|-\n| 1999 || ''[[Onegin (film)|Onegin]]'' || Vladimir Lensky || [[Martha Fiennes]]||Based on the verse drama ''[[Eugene Onegin]]'' by [[Alexander Pushkin]]\n|-\n| 1999 || ''Sunset Heights'' || Luke Bradley || Colm Villa ||\n|-\n| 2000 || ''The Announcement'' || Ross || [[Troy Miller]]||\n|-\n| 2000 || ''[[Space Cowboys]]'' || Young Frank || [[Clint Eastwood]] ||\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Possession (2002 film)|Possession]]'' || Fergus Wolfe || [[Neil LaBute]]||Based on the novel ''[[Possession: A Romance]]'' by [[A. S. Byatt]]\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Die Another Day]]'' || [[Gustav Graves]] || [[Lee Tamahori]]||Based on the characters of [[Ian Fleming]]\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[Terkel in Trouble]]'' || Voice of Justin || Ray Gillon (English version) || Animated film\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Midsummer Dream]]'' || Voice of Demetrius || Ray Gillon (English version) || Animated film Based on the play ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]'' by [[Shakespeare]]\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Mangal Pandey: 